  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Northern Badghis WASH Assistance Project</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In order to ensure that lives are saved in the areas of highest need (SO1) and support vulnerable people to build their resilience (SO3), WVI is proposing to provide life-saving WASH assistance to 6 communities / 1285 households / 9,936 (4,888 males,  5,048  females) people in Ghormach and Bala Murghab districts of Badghis Province.  Both districts are hard-to-reach (HTR) locations, according to the HRP.  

There is a significant need for WASH interventions in these locations, which are frequently impacted by conflict natural disasters and currently under-served by humanitarian actors.  According to the most recent 2019 REACH assessment, 42% of assessed settlements in Ghormach and 53% of assessment settlements in Bala Murghab have had their main water sources destroyed, damaged or dried due to natural disasters.  According to a 2019 WV multi-sector needs assessment, 100% of households in Ghormach are consuming water from unprotected sources. Hand washing with soap is not widely practiced, with 0% of households in Ghormach possessing soap for hand washing (WVI, 2019).  The lack of clean drinking water and poor hygiene practices is considered a key contributor to high diarrhea rates.  In Ghormach district, the diarrhea rate among children under 5 was 54% compared to the 29% national average (WVI, 2019 ADHS, 2015).  

WV will address outcome 1.9 of the HRP (WASH assistance is delivered to women, men, boys and girls living in hard-to-reach areas) and outcome 3.7 (Vulnerable people have access to safe drinking water as a result of resilient activities) by providing drinking water via 6 solar-powered drinking water networks connected to deep boreholes in HRT locations in Bala Murghab and Ghormach.  WASH assistance will also be provided in HTR locations through hygiene training and Family Hygiene Kits to all households so that they are able to practice essential hygiene behaviors such as hand washing.  By providing clean drinking water and improved hygiene practices, diarrhea and malnutrition rates will decline, thus &#x201C;saving lives in the areas of highest need&#x201D; (HRP SO1).  Provision of water supply networks to these locations that are frequently exposed to drought will also ensure that &quot;vulnerable people are supported to build their resilience&quot; (HRP SO3).</narrative>
  </description>
